WEBVTT

00:01.066 --> 00:02.500
♪ ♪

00:02.500 --> 00:04.900
Still persisting
with your sugar boycott?

00:04.900 --> 00:06.900
Are you not biting the hand
that feeds you?

00:06.900 --> 00:08.600
♪ ♪

00:08.600 --> 00:10.000
CHARLOTTE:
It seems Mr. Colbourne

00:10.000 --> 00:11.700
is a better man than I'd given
him credit for.

00:11.700 --> 00:13.066
He is just grieving
his late wife.

00:13.066 --> 00:14.433
LENNOX:
Her name was Lucy.

00:14.433 --> 00:15.966
Colbourne stole her from me.

00:15.966 --> 00:17.533
And then he destroyed her.

00:17.533 --> 00:20.400
BEATRICE (quietly):
The Army are running up
vast amounts of credit.

00:20.400 --> 00:21.900
The shopkeepers are up in arms.

00:21.900 --> 00:23.166
ALISON:
Captain Carter spoke of

00:23.166 --> 00:24.366
his brave actions at Bidassoa.

00:24.366 --> 00:26.566
Did he now?

00:26.566 --> 00:29.500
♪ ♪

00:31.000 --> 00:35.566
♪ ♪

00:40.833 --> 00:45.133
♪ ♪

00:50.933 --> 00:54.500
♪ ♪

00:56.366 --> 01:01.566
♪ ♪

01:15.633 --> 01:20.100
♪ ♪

01:25.700 --> 01:29.466
(horses snorting)

01:29.466 --> 01:33.333
♪ ♪

01:37.833 --> 01:39.366
(snorting)

01:44.300 --> 01:46.866
CARTER:
Colonel.

01:46.866 --> 01:48.600
May I beg a moment
of your time later?

01:48.600 --> 01:50.733
I have an important matter
to discuss.

01:51.600 --> 01:54.166
Of course, Captain.

01:55.066 --> 01:56.533
What was so important?

01:56.533 --> 01:58.900
I shall require
his permission, Fraser,

01:58.900 --> 02:01.600
if I am to ask
for Miss Heywood's hand.

02:01.600 --> 02:03.733
(horse nickers)

02:07.200 --> 02:08.833
Look, Charlotte.

02:08.833 --> 02:10.433
Do you suppose my captain
is among them?

02:10.433 --> 02:12.200
CHARLOTTE:
Your captain?

02:12.200 --> 02:13.566
He is mine.

02:13.566 --> 02:16.000
His letters leave no room
for doubt.

02:16.000 --> 02:18.200
And I am his.

02:18.200 --> 02:20.066
How can you be certain?

02:20.066 --> 02:22.766
After so brief
an acquaintance?

02:22.766 --> 02:25.233
I know he has the soul
of a poet.

02:25.233 --> 02:27.766
And he's handsome and brave;

02:27.766 --> 02:29.200
a man who saved 50 soldiers

02:29.200 --> 02:30.333
from drowning.
Drowning.

02:30.333 --> 02:33.966
Yes, you have mentioned it,
but...

02:33.966 --> 02:35.600
Sometimes it's hard
to gain a sense

02:35.600 --> 02:37.966
of a man's true character.

02:37.966 --> 02:39.500
One may form an impression,
and then

02:39.500 --> 02:43.900
hear something
which counteracts it.

02:44.766 --> 02:46.300
Charlotte?

02:46.300 --> 02:48.933
Yesterday,
Colonel Lennox told me something

02:48.933 --> 02:51.500
deeply troubling about
Mr. Colbourne.

02:51.500 --> 02:53.600
I don't know
what to make of it.

02:53.600 --> 02:54.700
You can surely trust the
colonel.

02:54.700 --> 02:57.900
♪ ♪

03:04.900 --> 03:07.600
You returned home late
last night, my dear.

03:07.600 --> 03:09.633
I'd gone to bed.

03:09.633 --> 03:11.533
Did you manage to settle matters
with the colonel?

03:11.533 --> 03:13.300
Well, actually, I,

03:13.300 --> 03:15.333
I found him rather busy
and surrounded by his men.

03:15.333 --> 03:16.900
He invited

03:16.900 --> 03:19.600
me to join them for,
for a drink, so, uh,

03:19.600 --> 03:21.400
well, it hardly seemed

03:21.400 --> 03:22.900
the right moment
to bring it up.

03:22.900 --> 03:24.200
ARTHUR:
Perhaps I should have come.

03:24.200 --> 03:25.800
For moral support.

03:25.800 --> 03:28.533
Yes, I rather wish you had,
Arthur.

03:28.533 --> 03:30.466
MARY:
We cannot let the poor
shopkeepers

03:30.466 --> 03:33.900
go unpaid for another day.
No, quite right,
my dear.

03:33.900 --> 03:35.933
I, I shall summon the colonel
this morning and, uh,

03:35.933 --> 03:37.866
demand he does
the honorable thing.

03:37.866 --> 03:40.400
(slaps table, chuckles):
That's the spirit!

03:40.400 --> 03:42.900
(bell ringing)

03:42.900 --> 03:44.133
♪ ♪

03:44.133 --> 03:45.400
I don't understand why
we had to run

03:45.400 --> 03:47.000
all the way here.
I just need
to speak to them.

03:47.000 --> 03:48.066
I need to speak
to them first.

03:48.066 --> 03:49.433
BEATRICE:
Really?

03:50.633 --> 03:53.033
I've had word
from my father's lawyer.

03:53.033 --> 03:56.533
He's discovered what Sidney
was doing in Antigua.

03:56.533 --> 04:01.100
♪ ♪

04:20.366 --> 04:23.500
EDWARD:
Not a word of this
to anyone.

04:23.500 --> 04:25.500
(snaps):
And you'll keep an eye out

04:25.500 --> 04:27.266
for anything that could be
of use to me.

04:27.266 --> 04:28.933
Of course, sir.

04:35.266 --> 04:37.233
GEORGIANA:
The man claimed

04:37.233 --> 04:39.900
he was a relative of my
father's.

04:39.900 --> 04:41.933
He argued that because of my
maternity,

04:41.933 --> 04:44.766
I was unfit to receive my
inheritance.

04:44.766 --> 04:47.533
Questioned my moral character,
and that of my mother.

04:47.533 --> 04:49.100
ARTHUR:
Who is this

04:49.100 --> 04:50.833
odious man?

04:50.833 --> 04:52.200
We've yet
to learn his name.

04:52.200 --> 04:56.766
But mercifully, his suit failed
in the Antiguan courts.

04:56.766 --> 04:59.100
If only because of your
brother's efforts.

04:59.100 --> 05:00.600
Dear Sidney.

05:00.600 --> 05:02.100
GEORGIANA:
If there is one relative

05:02.100 --> 05:03.933
who believes I am unworthy,

05:03.933 --> 05:05.600
who's to say there won't be
a dozen more?

05:05.600 --> 05:07.066
MARY:
Then you must
prove them wrong.

05:07.066 --> 05:10.400
In how you live your life,
in, in how you conduct yourself.

05:10.400 --> 05:13.600
You are suggesting the fault
lies with me?

05:14.866 --> 05:17.866
Were I white and a man, who
would question my legitimacy?

05:17.866 --> 05:19.800
I am afraid there will
always be those

05:19.800 --> 05:21.366
who seek to undermine you,
my dear.

05:21.366 --> 05:24.533
We are merely asking
you not to fuel the fire.

05:24.533 --> 05:27.600
♪ ♪

05:27.600 --> 05:29.600
(baby crying)

05:29.600 --> 05:36.833
♪ ♪

05:36.833 --> 05:41.066
(baby continues crying)

05:41.066 --> 05:43.400
(crying)

05:43.400 --> 05:45.866
(door opens)
LADY DENHAM:
Has Dr. Fuchs' tincture

05:45.866 --> 05:47.066
had any discernible effect?

05:47.066 --> 05:49.366
ESTHER:
It's rather too soon
to tell.

05:49.366 --> 05:51.066
LADY DENHAM:
Oh, goodness me.

05:51.066 --> 05:53.833
(baby crying)

05:53.833 --> 05:56.066
(fussing)

05:56.066 --> 05:59.000
Oh, there is no sight
more moving

05:59.000 --> 06:01.400
than a new mother
with her child.

06:01.400 --> 06:03.500
So I'm told.
(baby fussing)

06:03.500 --> 06:07.833
How is he?
Beautiful.

06:07.833 --> 06:09.500
Oh, as well as the Denham chin,

06:09.500 --> 06:11.500
he appears to have
the Denham voice:

06:11.500 --> 06:13.133
not afraid to ask
for what he wants.

06:13.133 --> 06:16.233
I suspect he is hungry.

06:16.233 --> 06:19.766
Indeed-- Martha?

06:24.166 --> 06:26.133
I've given instructions
for the groundskeeper's cottage

06:26.133 --> 06:28.100
to be cleared.

06:28.100 --> 06:29.100
It's been unoccupied

06:29.100 --> 06:31.433
for a few years,
so it's a little damp,

06:31.433 --> 06:33.833
but it'll do,
until we find somewhere

06:33.833 --> 06:35.366
more permanent to put you.

06:35.366 --> 06:37.400
It is kind of you to think
of us at all.

06:37.400 --> 06:39.366
And I'd prefer you to be
ensconced there

06:39.366 --> 06:41.233
as soon as possible.

06:41.233 --> 06:43.500
Because tomorrow is my annual
garden party.

06:43.500 --> 06:46.000
And much as it pains me

06:46.000 --> 06:48.433
to have my grounds
trampled on,

06:48.433 --> 06:49.966
it is the highlight
of the season.

06:49.966 --> 06:53.166
Don't worry, Aunt,
we shall remain invisible.

06:53.166 --> 06:55.733
I'm glad we understand
each other.

06:58.333 --> 07:00.500
♪ ♪

07:00.500 --> 07:02.300
LADY DENHAM:
Ah.

07:04.200 --> 07:06.000
Has anything come for me?

07:06.000 --> 07:10.233
No, still nothing, I'm afraid.

07:10.233 --> 07:15.300
I'm sure you'll hear from
Lord Babington soon enough.

07:17.466 --> 07:21.466
♪ ♪

07:21.466 --> 07:25.066
(dishes clanking)

07:25.066 --> 07:27.300
Mrs. Wheatley?

07:29.533 --> 07:34.000
(playing lively tune)

07:42.800 --> 07:43.833
What are you doing?

07:43.833 --> 07:44.833
(gasps)

07:44.833 --> 07:46.533
If your uncle hears you...

07:46.533 --> 07:48.566
It was he
who unlocked it.

07:48.566 --> 07:50.600
He who had it tuned.

07:50.600 --> 07:52.000
Oh!

07:52.000 --> 07:53.866
Well...

07:53.866 --> 07:56.833
That is unexpected.

07:56.833 --> 07:58.033
But welcome.

07:58.033 --> 08:00.033
Now we can have dancing lessons.

08:00.033 --> 08:01.100
Yes!

08:01.100 --> 08:03.133
AUGUSTA:
Hm.

08:07.433 --> 08:12.400
(birds chirping)

08:14.000 --> 08:17.166
I thought I commissioned
a painting, not a sketch.

08:17.166 --> 08:19.700
I have to discover who you
are first,

08:19.700 --> 08:23.066
before I can commit
to the canvas.

08:25.266 --> 08:28.800
Perhaps we could try you...

08:28.800 --> 08:31.066
Seated.

08:33.633 --> 08:36.800
I prefer to stand.

08:36.800 --> 08:38.733
Of course.

08:38.733 --> 08:40.000
As befits your position

08:40.000 --> 08:42.200
in society.

08:42.200 --> 08:43.700
Gracious!

08:43.700 --> 08:45.533
CHARLES:
I hope you're not shocked,
Miss Hankins.

08:45.533 --> 08:48.133
By no means, sir.

08:48.133 --> 08:49.266
Were Adam and Eve not naked

08:49.266 --> 08:50.633
in the Garden of Eden,

08:50.633 --> 08:53.500
baring all before God?

08:53.500 --> 08:58.066
One might say this is the Lord's
true vision of us.

08:58.066 --> 08:59.900
GEORGIANA:
Don't give the artist

08:59.900 --> 09:01.400
any ideas.

09:01.400 --> 09:03.233
CHARLES:
I'm not asking you
to bare your skin,

09:03.233 --> 09:07.066
Miss Lambe,
but to bare your soul.

09:08.600 --> 09:13.333
You offer me Miss Lambe.

09:13.333 --> 09:17.100
But I wish to find Georgiana.

09:19.033 --> 09:22.400
You will address me as
Miss Lambe.

09:25.433 --> 09:27.733
(exhales)

09:27.733 --> 09:31.666
♪ ♪

09:39.100 --> 09:40.966
(door opens)

09:40.966 --> 09:44.166
Here are some socks
to keep him warm.

09:44.166 --> 09:46.200
CLARA:
It is not like you
to show me

09:46.200 --> 09:48.733
such generosity,
Esther.

09:48.733 --> 09:51.533
They're not for you,
they're for George.

09:51.533 --> 09:55.033
Since you lack the means
to provide for him.

09:55.033 --> 09:57.333
(George crying)
What does he want now?

09:57.333 --> 09:58.900
The nurse only just fed him.

09:58.900 --> 10:02.033
Martha?
(footsteps approaching)

10:02.033 --> 10:03.966
Will you take the child
for a walk?

10:03.966 --> 10:08.400
I cannot bear that noise.
Or I could take him.

10:13.466 --> 10:16.333
(Esther cooing, George crying)

10:17.800 --> 10:21.000
(snoring quietly)

10:24.300 --> 10:25.333
No.

10:25.333 --> 10:26.700
(sighs)

10:26.700 --> 10:28.500
No, you are so stiff,
I might as well

10:28.500 --> 10:29.766
be drawing
Lady Denham.

10:29.766 --> 10:30.933
Then perhaps you should.

10:30.933 --> 10:33.966
I am looking for passion!

10:33.966 --> 10:35.600
Emotion, honesty!

10:35.600 --> 10:37.633
Not some stale,

10:37.633 --> 10:39.200
lifeless rendering.

10:39.200 --> 10:42.000
(sighs)

10:42.000 --> 10:44.833
Tell me something true
about yourself.

10:45.900 --> 10:47.333
What?

10:48.200 --> 10:49.300
Your childhood.

10:49.300 --> 10:51.733
A happy memory.

10:51.733 --> 10:54.366
Talk of your father,
your mother.

10:54.366 --> 10:55.700
They are both dead.

10:55.700 --> 10:58.133
(sighs)

10:58.133 --> 11:00.366
What did you dream
of last night?

11:03.233 --> 11:05.533
That is none
of your concern.

11:05.533 --> 11:06.666
There.

11:06.666 --> 11:09.400
That is something.

11:09.400 --> 11:11.733
Your mask slipped.

11:14.200 --> 11:15.800
Come, Miss Hankins.
(starts)

11:15.800 --> 11:17.600
We're leaving.

11:17.600 --> 11:21.566
♪ ♪

11:26.733 --> 11:31.200
Two, three, four-- turn.
(pianoforte playing hesitantly)

11:31.200 --> 11:34.033
(both laugh)
One, two,

11:34.033 --> 11:37.533
three, four.

11:37.533 --> 11:40.433
Good.

11:40.433 --> 11:42.966
Four, and...

11:42.966 --> 11:44.600
BOTH:
One.

11:44.600 --> 11:45.966
Two.

11:45.966 --> 11:46.966
Three.

11:46.966 --> 11:48.900
Four.

11:48.900 --> 11:50.000
One.

11:50.000 --> 11:51.233
CHARLOTTE:
Two...

11:52.533 --> 11:54.066
(chuckle)

11:57.300 --> 11:59.266
And a one, two, three,

11:59.266 --> 12:00.700
four, five, six,

12:00.700 --> 12:02.200
seven, eight, a one.

12:02.200 --> 12:04.733
CHARLOTTE AND AUGUSTA:
Two, three, four, five, six...

12:04.733 --> 12:06.933
Seven, turn...
(giggles)

12:06.933 --> 12:09.533
Mr. Colbourne.

12:09.533 --> 12:12.100
I was trying to teach Miss
Markham the cotillion,

12:12.100 --> 12:13.533
but, uh...

12:13.533 --> 12:16.166
We need a gentleman.

12:18.033 --> 12:20.000
No.
(chuckles)

12:20.000 --> 12:22.033
I won't be persuaded to dance,
I'm afraid.

12:22.033 --> 12:24.400
Not under
any circumstances.

12:24.400 --> 12:27.400
Augusta, I have decided
that you and I

12:27.400 --> 12:29.400
should attend Lady Denham's
garden party tomorrow.

12:30.966 --> 12:32.233
You have complained
long enough

12:32.233 --> 12:34.666
that you wish to be
introduced to society.

12:34.666 --> 12:36.933
Well, here is your chance.

12:38.633 --> 12:40.466
I shall also be attending.

12:40.466 --> 12:44.266
Then my dread of the occasion
has somewhat lessened.

12:46.133 --> 12:47.633
AUGUSTA:
But,

12:47.633 --> 12:50.200
what am I going to wear, Uncle?

12:51.400 --> 12:53.233
There are wardrobes full
of your aunt's dresses

12:53.233 --> 12:54.933
in the East Wing.

12:54.933 --> 12:57.233
Perhaps you might find something
that fits you there.

12:59.000 --> 13:01.433
I shall leave you ladies
to your cotillion.

13:01.433 --> 13:04.900
♪ ♪

13:09.933 --> 13:12.000
(birds chirping)

13:12.000 --> 13:17.533
(George cooing)

13:17.533 --> 13:24.133
♪ ♪

13:32.366 --> 13:34.533
Is that my child?

13:37.433 --> 13:39.666
You swore you had nothing
to do with him.

13:39.666 --> 13:42.533
Him?

13:42.533 --> 13:44.033
I have a son?

13:45.166 --> 13:46.966
May I see him?

13:46.966 --> 13:48.766
Please, Esther.

13:48.766 --> 13:50.833
Even just for a moment.

13:56.466 --> 14:00.233
(George fussing)

14:02.700 --> 14:03.766
Oh, but he is handsome.

14:03.766 --> 14:08.033
(cooing)

14:08.033 --> 14:10.200
There can be no denying
that he's mine.

14:12.366 --> 14:14.100
My son.

14:14.100 --> 14:18.366
How strange it is
to say those words.

14:18.366 --> 14:21.266
Thank you, Esther.

14:24.200 --> 14:26.466
Truly.

14:30.600 --> 14:33.866
(man yelling)

14:33.866 --> 14:36.200
(metal clanging)

14:36.200 --> 14:37.700
It is done, Fraser.

14:37.700 --> 14:39.866
I have the blessing of our
commanding officer.

14:41.166 --> 14:43.466
You can't do this.
Why not?

14:43.466 --> 14:45.066
I love her, she loves me.

14:45.066 --> 14:46.433
I've heard you say
that before.

14:46.433 --> 14:49.733
More than once.
This is not the same--
she's different.

14:49.733 --> 14:51.500
But you are not.

14:51.500 --> 14:53.333
You are the same Carter
who fell in love

14:53.333 --> 14:55.300
with all those other girls
in all those other towns.

14:55.300 --> 14:57.600
Can a young man not grow up

14:57.600 --> 15:00.233
and realize the qualities
he requires in a wife?

15:00.233 --> 15:03.166
How about the qualities a wife
may require in a husband?

15:03.166 --> 15:05.433
Such as honesty.
Fraser...

15:05.433 --> 15:07.500
You have wooed her under
false pretenses.

15:07.500 --> 15:09.566
A little aggrandizement
of my past.

15:09.566 --> 15:10.666
Damn it, man,

15:10.666 --> 15:12.300
you have lied to her!
Lies

15:12.300 --> 15:15.300
which will make no odds
to our future happiness.

15:15.300 --> 15:16.966
And if she were to find out?

15:18.000 --> 15:20.466
And why should she have to?

15:26.133 --> 15:30.633
♪ ♪

15:33.066 --> 15:35.733
He fell asleep in my arms.

15:35.733 --> 15:36.700
Will you take him?

15:36.700 --> 15:39.333
You can place him in his crib.

15:39.333 --> 15:41.866
The only time I've seen you hold
him is in front of Lady Denham.

15:41.866 --> 15:43.266
It's almost as if you're playing
the role of mother

15:43.266 --> 15:44.500
for her benefit alone.

15:44.500 --> 15:47.566
Just because I am not fussing
and cooing over him

15:47.566 --> 15:48.933
as you seem to be.

15:48.933 --> 15:50.866
How can you not?

15:50.866 --> 15:53.533
(cooing)

15:53.533 --> 15:55.200
Look at him, Clara.

15:55.200 --> 15:58.100
He's perfect.

15:58.100 --> 16:01.533
(voice cracking):
If he were mine,
I would never let him go.

16:04.800 --> 16:06.933
Esther?

16:09.500 --> 16:12.400
Don't you realize
how lucky you are?

16:12.400 --> 16:14.333
Do you know what some women

16:14.333 --> 16:17.300
would give to have a child?

16:19.500 --> 16:22.166
Yet you barely even look at him.

16:26.900 --> 16:31.366
When he was born, you wept.

16:31.366 --> 16:35.933
Now I understand why.

16:35.933 --> 16:39.466
How cruel fate can be.

16:44.466 --> 16:47.066
TOM:
This is an initial plan
for the barracks.

16:47.066 --> 16:50.533
You can see the quarters are
more than generous.

16:50.533 --> 16:54.466
And the mess area?
Virtually a banquet hall.

16:54.466 --> 16:57.233
Most impressive, Mr. Parker.

16:57.233 --> 16:58.466
Yes.

17:00.633 --> 17:03.533
But, uh...

17:03.533 --> 17:05.233
That is not the only reason

17:05.233 --> 17:06.600
that I invited you here,
Colonel.

17:06.600 --> 17:09.033
I'm certain it's
an oversight,

17:09.033 --> 17:12.600
but evidently your company
has been running up

17:12.600 --> 17:13.800
rather a lot of credit

17:13.800 --> 17:15.233
across town.

17:15.233 --> 17:17.833
The mess dinner, for instance,
has yet to be paid for.

17:17.833 --> 17:18.966
A sizeable amount.

17:18.966 --> 17:22.966
Now, we really can't have our
shopkeepers

17:22.966 --> 17:23.966
going out of business,

17:23.966 --> 17:26.466
as I'm sure
you will agree.

17:26.466 --> 17:28.066
Come now.

17:28.066 --> 17:30.666
Every gentleman has his debts,
don't they, Tom?

17:30.666 --> 17:34.233
But it's rather bad form
to bring them up.

17:34.233 --> 17:37.466
Perhaps you might pour us
a drink instead.

17:40.000 --> 17:42.200
(sighs)

17:42.200 --> 17:43.200
And tell me.

17:43.200 --> 17:45.266
What of Miss Heywood?

17:45.266 --> 17:47.800
Has she reconsidered her
position with Mr. Colbourne?

17:48.900 --> 17:50.433
No.

17:50.433 --> 17:52.900
I believe she is there even
as we speak.

17:52.900 --> 17:54.900
(softly):
It's a great shame.

17:54.900 --> 18:00.266
I hoped by now she might
have seen sense.

18:00.266 --> 18:01.666
(exhales)

18:01.666 --> 18:04.766
♪ ♪

18:04.766 --> 18:08.200
AUGUSTA:
It's the thing I remember best
about my aunt.

18:08.200 --> 18:09.900
Her beautiful dresses.

18:09.900 --> 18:12.600
She was always so elegant,

18:12.600 --> 18:15.033
but this,
this is my favorite.

18:15.033 --> 18:16.866
I remember her wearing it to
a ball in London

18:16.866 --> 18:17.833
with my mother and father.

18:17.833 --> 18:20.133
And Mr. Colbourne?

18:20.133 --> 18:23.100
(slowly):
He rarely came to London
with her.

18:23.100 --> 18:25.800
He's always been
solitary.

18:25.800 --> 18:27.933
How do I look, Miss Heywood?

18:27.933 --> 18:29.666
Like a lady.

18:31.233 --> 18:32.600
I fear it won't fasten.

18:32.600 --> 18:35.200
I'm not as slender
as Aunt Lucy was.

18:35.200 --> 18:38.800
You're not wearing the right
undergarments, that's all.

18:40.866 --> 18:43.466
Miss Heywood.

18:43.466 --> 18:46.700
Do you think
I'm ready?
For what?

18:46.700 --> 18:48.933
Society.

18:48.933 --> 18:52.633
I know I can be ill-mannered
and, and disagreeable.

18:52.633 --> 18:55.333
What if I give a poor account
of myself?

18:55.333 --> 18:57.400
You won't.

18:57.400 --> 19:00.866
I have every faith
in you.

19:00.866 --> 19:03.600
Anyway, it is your job to ready
me for society,

19:03.600 --> 19:06.766
so if I am not, then the blame
lies with you.

19:06.766 --> 19:08.366
(chuckles)

19:08.366 --> 19:10.500
Although I'm almost certain
my uncle will change his mind.

19:10.500 --> 19:13.466
I won't believe it
until we're there.

19:15.400 --> 19:16.500
Oh!

19:16.500 --> 19:17.966
What are you doing?

19:17.966 --> 19:21.700
LEO:
This is my mother's dress.

19:21.700 --> 19:27.800
So, in a way, it's like
I'm hugging her, isn't it?

19:30.200 --> 19:33.000
Yes, Leo.

19:33.000 --> 19:37.433
I suppose it is.

19:37.433 --> 19:39.533
(birds chirping)

19:44.700 --> 19:49.866
♪ ♪

19:56.166 --> 19:58.233
(sighs)

20:01.300 --> 20:06.933
♪ ♪

20:19.333 --> 20:20.833
(exhales)

20:21.900 --> 20:23.500
(gasping)

20:23.500 --> 20:26.066
(wincing)

20:26.066 --> 20:28.700
(breathes deeply)

20:28.700 --> 20:35.400
♪ ♪

20:41.366 --> 20:45.066
♪ ♪

20:50.233 --> 20:51.600
(exhales)

20:51.600 --> 20:56.300
(people talking,
music playing in background)

21:07.466 --> 21:12.600
(conversations and music
continue)

21:21.500 --> 21:24.366
Such grandeur, Lady Denham.

21:24.366 --> 21:27.066
ARTHUR:
What a magnificent buffet table.

21:27.066 --> 21:28.900
Yes, how typically generous of
you this is.

21:28.900 --> 21:31.366
Don't remind me.

21:31.366 --> 21:35.066
If I dwell too long on what this
is costing, I get palpitations.

21:35.066 --> 21:38.033
Lady Babington.

21:38.033 --> 21:39.066
Afternoon, miladies.

21:39.066 --> 21:41.500
Has your nephew arrived yet,
Lady Denham?

21:41.500 --> 21:42.900
No, he was not invited.

21:42.900 --> 21:45.200
Oh, dear.

21:45.200 --> 21:48.833
I hope I do not detect
some family discord.

21:48.833 --> 21:50.133
ESTHER:
Not in the least.

21:50.133 --> 21:52.500
We're as close
as Cain and Abel.

21:57.533 --> 21:58.900
LADY DENHAM:
Miss Lambe.

21:58.900 --> 22:00.766
How honored we are

22:00.766 --> 22:03.566
to have the richest woman
in Sanditon among us.

22:03.566 --> 22:06.666
'Tis kind of you to invite me,
milady.

22:06.666 --> 22:08.133
I insist you enjoy yourself.

22:08.133 --> 22:10.233
You must avail yourself of all
the entertainments.

22:10.233 --> 22:12.366
And the food, of course.

22:12.366 --> 22:14.400
I had a cake made specially.

22:14.400 --> 22:18.100
♪ ♪

22:19.333 --> 22:22.266
How thoughtful.

22:24.366 --> 22:27.200
She must have forgotten the
sugar boycott.

22:27.200 --> 22:29.066
How unfortunate.

22:29.066 --> 22:30.666
She did not
forget.

22:30.666 --> 22:31.733
Try not to rise
to it,

22:31.733 --> 22:34.033
my dear.

22:34.033 --> 22:37.500
I think I spy
my captain.

22:39.833 --> 22:42.200
CHARLOTTE:
Why must Lady Denham

22:42.200 --> 22:43.266
be so spiteful?

22:43.266 --> 22:45.533
She's trying to put me
in my place.

22:45.533 --> 22:47.166
She thinks me a hypocrite.

22:47.166 --> 22:49.866
It's hardly hypocritical
to stand up for what's right.

22:49.866 --> 22:54.100
I am all too aware of the
suffering my fortune represents.

22:54.100 --> 22:57.800
That's exactly why I cannot stay
silent.

22:59.366 --> 23:01.366
Who is that man?

23:03.600 --> 23:06.133
CHARLOTTE:
It is Mr. Colbourne.

23:06.133 --> 23:09.266
That is Mr. Colbourne?

23:13.266 --> 23:19.733
♪ ♪

23:19.733 --> 23:21.866
Are these gardens not
magnificent?

23:21.866 --> 23:25.066
Not as magnificent as
the company which adorns them.

23:25.066 --> 23:26.500
But you do not have
a drink.

23:26.500 --> 23:28.800
We must remedy that
at once.

23:29.966 --> 23:32.633
He is always so attentive.

23:32.633 --> 23:33.933
He reminds me of a puppy
I once had.

23:33.933 --> 23:38.466
What does it take to make a man
so cynical, Captain?

23:38.466 --> 23:39.733
Have you never known
tender feelings

23:39.733 --> 23:42.200
of your own?
Absolutely not.

23:42.200 --> 23:44.400
I am a typical soldier;

23:44.400 --> 23:47.333
spartan, coarse, uncouth.

23:47.333 --> 23:49.166
I suspect there
is a beating heart

23:49.166 --> 23:50.600
somewhere beneath that uniform.

23:50.600 --> 23:54.033
You will search in vain.

23:54.033 --> 23:55.800
There is someone.

23:57.100 --> 23:58.800
I knew it--
what is her name?

23:58.800 --> 24:01.333
I cannot say.
Then...

24:01.333 --> 24:03.133
Tell me, what is she like?

24:03.133 --> 24:05.400
Oh...

24:05.400 --> 24:08.666
She's a rare creature indeed.

24:08.666 --> 24:11.033
Delicate, yet strong.

24:11.033 --> 24:13.366
Guileless, yet wise.

24:13.366 --> 24:15.300
But in truth,

24:15.300 --> 24:19.466
I am quite undone in her
company.

24:19.466 --> 24:22.633
Does she know of your feelings?
No, no, no.

24:22.633 --> 24:25.400
No good could come of that,
Miss Heywood.

24:25.400 --> 24:28.500
Her heart belongs elsewhere.

24:28.500 --> 24:33.600
Besides, I know she could never
look on me with tenderness.

24:33.600 --> 24:37.000
I believe the right person
is out there for all of us.

24:37.000 --> 24:39.233
Happily, I have found mine.

24:39.233 --> 24:41.800
Miss Heywood.

24:46.766 --> 24:48.400
Mr. Colbourne.

24:48.400 --> 24:50.400
What an unexpected pleasure.

24:50.400 --> 24:52.200
Lady Denham.

24:52.200 --> 24:55.066
My niece,
Miss Augusta Markham.

24:55.066 --> 24:56.633
Oh, she's a pretty little thing.

24:56.633 --> 24:59.433
I'd keep her away from
the soldiers if I was you.

24:59.433 --> 25:01.700
I fully intend to.

25:01.700 --> 25:05.300
I hope you're going to enter
the archery competition.

25:05.300 --> 25:07.833
Your late father won the
Silver Arrow

25:07.833 --> 25:09.033
three years running.

25:09.033 --> 25:11.800
I'm nothing like my father.

25:11.800 --> 25:14.133
No, well, that's a relief.

25:14.133 --> 25:16.533
It will save me a fortune
in wine.

25:23.633 --> 25:30.700
♪ ♪

25:30.700 --> 25:32.600
Miss Markham.

25:32.600 --> 25:33.833
You look so elegant.

25:33.833 --> 25:38.366
And, well, you look nothing
like a governess.

25:38.366 --> 25:40.633
That's high praise indeed,
coming from Augusta.

25:41.666 --> 25:42.866
LENNOX:
Lady Denham.

25:42.866 --> 25:44.833
Oh, Colonel Lennox.

25:44.833 --> 25:46.733
You are most welcome.

25:46.733 --> 25:48.100
LENNOX:
Thank you, milady.

25:48.100 --> 25:49.133
Are you having
a pleasant day?

25:49.133 --> 25:50.333
Very pleasant, thank you.

25:50.333 --> 25:52.566
We've been very lucky
with the weather.

25:52.566 --> 25:54.200
I should congratulate you
on a...

25:54.200 --> 25:55.533
Hm.

25:58.533 --> 26:00.366
Please excuse me.

26:02.166 --> 26:04.200
I'm so glad the colonel visited
this morning.

26:04.200 --> 26:06.800
I trust he agreed
to settle the debts.

26:06.800 --> 26:10.366
Well, he hasn't
exactly said so, my dear.

26:10.366 --> 26:13.433
Not in so many words.

26:15.633 --> 26:17.033
Mr. Colbourne.

26:17.033 --> 26:22.066
♪ ♪

26:22.066 --> 26:23.233
Miss Heywood.

26:24.500 --> 26:26.500
COLBOURNE:
I wasn't aware

26:26.500 --> 26:29.400
that you and my governess
were acquainted.

26:29.400 --> 26:30.933
I would presume Miss Heywood
to be a friend.

26:32.033 --> 26:34.000
Would you indeed?
Hm.

26:42.433 --> 26:44.133
Excuse me.

26:46.333 --> 26:49.600
You chose not to heed
my warning, I see.

26:51.166 --> 26:54.333
Is it not possible
he has changed?

26:54.333 --> 26:55.400
I very much doubt it.

26:55.400 --> 27:00.700
But for your sake,
I shall try to be civil.

27:05.233 --> 27:06.566
(knocks)

27:09.100 --> 27:10.266
May I come in?

27:10.266 --> 27:12.733
Absolutely not.

27:13.800 --> 27:14.766
Then,

27:14.766 --> 27:16.933
I shall have to say it
out here.

27:19.533 --> 27:23.933
Clara Brereton,
will you marry me?

27:26.900 --> 27:28.400
It was a mistake
for us to come.

27:28.400 --> 27:29.800
I had no idea
you and that man

27:29.800 --> 27:32.166
were so
intimately acquainted.

27:32.166 --> 27:33.466
Whatever the history
between...

27:33.466 --> 27:36.233
What do you know of
our history?

27:36.233 --> 27:39.266
Only that there is
clearly some animosity.

27:39.266 --> 27:41.066
But if Colonel Lennox

27:41.066 --> 27:42.400
can have the grace
to set that aside

27:42.400 --> 27:45.466
for one afternoon,
surely you can do the same.

27:45.466 --> 27:47.933
For Miss Markham's sake,
if nothing else.

27:50.466 --> 27:53.766
Very well.

27:53.766 --> 27:57.566
We will stay a short while,
but we shall keep our distance.

27:57.566 --> 28:00.666
You have been refusing to
acknowledge the child as yours.

28:00.666 --> 28:02.700
What changed
all of a sudden?

28:02.700 --> 28:03.766
I became a father.

28:03.766 --> 28:07.533
I do not want my son
growing up a bastard.

28:07.533 --> 28:09.166
In poverty, hidden away

28:09.166 --> 28:10.333
in some damp cottage.

28:10.333 --> 28:11.833
I want to make him respectable.

28:13.466 --> 28:16.500
If we marry,
he becomes a Denham.

28:16.500 --> 28:18.566
With you disinherited,
he is the next male heir.

28:18.566 --> 28:20.366
It's the kindest thing
we can do for him.

28:20.366 --> 28:22.366
For him?

28:22.366 --> 28:26.800
And I suppose we would
also benefit as a result.

28:28.600 --> 28:30.700
Huh, you've not
considered Esther.

28:30.700 --> 28:31.866
Even if we were to marry,

28:31.866 --> 28:32.966
the bulk of
Lady Denham's inheritance

28:32.966 --> 28:34.133
would still go to her.

28:36.033 --> 28:38.800
Don't you worry about Esther.

28:38.800 --> 28:41.266
I'm taking care of her.

28:41.266 --> 28:43.866
LADY DENHAM:
I've held it every year.

28:43.866 --> 28:45.400
(stammering):
Uh, did you know, Charlotte,

28:45.400 --> 28:46.566
that the, uh, the colonel

28:46.566 --> 28:48.400
faced Napoleon
himself at Waterloo?

28:48.400 --> 28:50.100
I hardly faced him alone,
Mr. Parker.

28:50.100 --> 28:52.366
Well, he can hardly be
that intimidating.

28:52.366 --> 28:54.133
I hear he only stands
this high.

28:54.133 --> 28:57.933
Yes, he was diminutive,
but a shrewd strategist.

28:59.366 --> 29:02.033
TOM:
It must have been
a bloody battle.

29:02.033 --> 29:03.233
Battle is always bloody.

29:03.233 --> 29:05.500
And yet there's
the greatest humanity

29:05.500 --> 29:06.800
to be found in it,

29:06.800 --> 29:09.300
for one must
count on one's men.

29:09.300 --> 29:10.966
Such as Captain Carter.

29:10.966 --> 29:12.800
I believe
he fought by your side?

29:12.800 --> 29:14.166
Captain Fraser,
you mean.

29:14.166 --> 29:16.400
No, Captain William Carter?

29:16.400 --> 29:18.666
You are mistaken,
Miss Heywood.

29:18.666 --> 29:20.166
Captain Carter
is just a boy.

29:20.166 --> 29:21.100
He's not yet been

29:21.100 --> 29:23.300
anywhere near
a battlefield.

29:28.000 --> 29:28.933
(bowstring creaking)

29:28.933 --> 29:30.433
(arrow releases,
hits target)

29:30.433 --> 29:32.000
SOLDIER:
Captain!

29:32.000 --> 29:33.766
Would you take a shot?

29:33.766 --> 29:34.866
Perhaps later.

29:34.866 --> 29:37.233
My dear Alison,

29:37.233 --> 29:38.933
would you care
to take a walk?

29:38.933 --> 29:40.933
There is something
I must ask you.

29:40.933 --> 29:41.933
Of course.

29:41.933 --> 29:42.866
FRASER:
Carter.

29:42.866 --> 29:44.666
The men are waiting
for you

29:44.666 --> 29:46.366
to take up the bow.

29:47.833 --> 29:49.566
You may have my turn,
Fraser.

29:49.566 --> 29:50.666
Ah.

29:50.666 --> 29:52.500
I'm not half
the archer you are.

29:52.500 --> 29:55.433
I would love to see you
loose an arrow.

29:55.433 --> 29:57.300
Our walk can wait a couple of
minutes, can it not?

29:57.300 --> 29:59.666
CARTER:
Very well.

29:59.666 --> 30:02.500
And then we will remove
ourselves from this company.

30:10.833 --> 30:13.033
He wishes to
speak to me alone.

30:13.033 --> 30:14.166
(arrow hits target)

30:14.166 --> 30:17.633
I hope I have not mistaken
his intent.

30:19.466 --> 30:22.533
Are you not happy for us,
Captain?

30:22.533 --> 30:24.366
Would that I could be,
Miss Heywood,

30:24.366 --> 30:26.300
and yet my conscience
compels me

30:26.300 --> 30:27.700
to urge caution.

30:27.700 --> 30:31.466
I fear you are letting your
experience cloud your judgment.

30:31.466 --> 30:34.166
I understand
your heart has suffered,

30:34.166 --> 30:35.800
but that is no reason to
doubt true love.

30:35.800 --> 30:38.133
Can you call it true,
Miss Heywood?

30:38.133 --> 30:40.433
When he barely understands
who you really are?

30:40.433 --> 30:42.700
You are not this
overly refined girl

30:42.700 --> 30:44.100
you pretend to be.

30:44.100 --> 30:45.600
You are a farmer's daughter.

30:46.666 --> 30:48.566
You are saying a farmer's
daughter

30:48.566 --> 30:52.266
is not worthy of becoming
an officer's wife?

30:52.266 --> 30:54.733
I knew you were brutish,
Captain.

30:54.733 --> 30:56.266
But I didn't know you were
heartless.

30:56.266 --> 31:00.133
♪ ♪

31:04.000 --> 31:06.800
EDWARD:
I know her weaknesses
better than anyone.

31:06.800 --> 31:09.466
The truth about Esther is,
deep down,

31:09.466 --> 31:11.933
she believes
she's unlovable.

31:11.933 --> 31:13.300
So, if she
starts to believe

31:13.300 --> 31:15.833
that Babington
had abandoned her,

31:15.833 --> 31:18.166
she would lose all reason.

31:18.166 --> 31:20.800
And our aunt is not going to
leave her money to

31:20.800 --> 31:23.400
someone whose faculties
are in doubt.

31:23.400 --> 31:24.800
Babington loves her.

31:24.800 --> 31:26.400
Why would he abandon her?

31:26.400 --> 31:29.000
It's tragic, really.

31:29.000 --> 31:30.366
Once he discovered
that she couldn't

31:30.366 --> 31:32.500
provide him with an heir,
he lost all interest.

31:32.500 --> 31:34.233
He hasn't written to her
in weeks.

31:34.233 --> 31:37.166
How do you know she...
I didn't.

31:37.166 --> 31:39.566
Though I had my suspicions.

31:39.566 --> 31:41.933
Thank you
for confirming it.

31:41.933 --> 31:45.900
♪ ♪

31:45.900 --> 31:48.533
She doesn't deserve this.

31:48.533 --> 31:50.600
She's been kind to me.

31:58.366 --> 32:03.166
Your friendship
is very touching.

32:03.166 --> 32:07.800
But rest assured,
she bears no love for you.

32:07.800 --> 32:13.366
All these presents and
ministrations are about power.

32:13.366 --> 32:16.766
Soon enough, she'll get bored
or, worse, resentful,

32:16.766 --> 32:22.000
because you have something
she so desperately wants.

32:22.000 --> 32:25.900
Then she'll push you aside,
because it'll be too painful.

32:25.900 --> 32:31.733
She will want you out of
Lady Denham's favor entirely.

32:31.733 --> 32:36.566
Then where will you be,
Clara?

32:36.566 --> 32:43.066
This cottage
will feel like a palace.

32:43.066 --> 32:44.733
(people talking in background)

32:44.733 --> 32:46.133
ALISON:
I cannot be long.

32:46.133 --> 32:47.466
Captain Carter waits for me.

32:47.466 --> 32:49.066
CHARLOTTE:
I fear Captain Carter

32:49.066 --> 32:51.433
has been less than honest
with you.

32:51.433 --> 32:53.100
What do you mean?

32:53.100 --> 32:55.100
(exhales)

32:55.100 --> 32:56.533
The colonel said
he was not at Bidassoa.

32:58.133 --> 33:00.300
He said he's never seen
battle of any kind.

33:00.300 --> 33:01.833
Of course he was.

33:01.833 --> 33:03.766
There were so many men there--
the colonel is misremembering.

33:03.766 --> 33:05.100
I do not think so.

33:05.100 --> 33:06.833
I know my William,

33:06.833 --> 33:09.233
and I know that he's
not a liar.

33:09.233 --> 33:12.200
You and Captain Fraser are
just jealous of what we have.

33:12.200 --> 33:13.533
I'm not going to let

33:13.533 --> 33:15.200
two bitter loveless cynics
spoil my happiness.

33:15.200 --> 33:16.166
Alison, you cannot...

33:16.166 --> 33:17.966
&nbsp;
Three loveless cynics.

33:17.966 --> 33:19.433
Alison.

33:26.266 --> 33:28.166
(applauding)

33:30.633 --> 33:36.333
(music playing)

33:37.066 --> 33:38.100
(mallet hits ball)

33:38.100 --> 33:39.133
Miss Heywood.

33:39.133 --> 33:41.366
You seem perturbed.

33:45.966 --> 33:49.333
My sister will
not listen to reason.

33:49.333 --> 33:52.666
If she finds the truth
inconvenient, she just

33:52.666 --> 33:56.433
disregards it.

33:56.433 --> 33:58.300
Well, in my experience,
a young woman's opinion,

33:58.300 --> 34:03.766
once formed,
is very hard to alter.

34:03.766 --> 34:06.100
(mallet hits ball)

34:06.100 --> 34:07.733
(crowd applauding)
(sighs)

34:07.733 --> 34:08.966
It's been a decade
since I've found myself

34:08.966 --> 34:12.266
in occasions such as this.

34:12.266 --> 34:14.700
I fear I've lost whatever
social graces I once owned.

34:14.700 --> 34:17.333
(mallet strikes ball)

34:17.333 --> 34:21.533
Perhaps you can remind me
how to hold a conversation.

34:21.533 --> 34:22.766
I thought
you had employed me

34:22.766 --> 34:26.033
to teach the girls,
Mr. Colbourne, not you.

34:26.033 --> 34:28.400
(chuckles)

34:28.400 --> 34:30.433
(birds twittering)

34:30.433 --> 34:31.966
(mallet hits ball)

34:31.966 --> 34:34.333
I believe
you have a rival.

34:34.333 --> 34:37.800
For the archery competition,
I mean.

34:37.800 --> 34:40.500
(chuckles):
Hm.

34:46.566 --> 34:51.633
(music playing)

34:53.500 --> 34:55.800
Bravo, Miss Heywood.

34:55.800 --> 34:57.533
(crowd applauding)

35:01.333 --> 35:03.500
(music continues)

35:05.200 --> 35:07.366
(Arthur exclaims
and laughs)

35:07.366 --> 35:08.633
ARTHUR:
Good shot, Miss Lambe.

35:08.633 --> 35:09.633
Wasn't it, Charles?

35:09.633 --> 35:10.766
I dare not disagree,

35:10.766 --> 35:12.366
given that Miss Lambe
is holding a mallet.

35:12.366 --> 35:14.200
(chuckling)

35:14.200 --> 35:17.133
Charles tells me
that your sitting was

35:17.133 --> 35:19.300
&nbsp;
less than successful.

35:19.300 --> 35:21.300
To put it mildly.

35:21.300 --> 35:22.366
The fact is, Arthur,

35:22.366 --> 35:24.433
you are entirely yourself
at all times.

35:24.433 --> 35:27.333
That is such a rare
and glorious thing.

35:28.266 --> 35:31.200
I know exactly
who I am, Mr. Lockhart.

35:31.200 --> 35:32.866
I hardly need you to tell me.

35:34.800 --> 35:36.966
(crowd applauding)

35:36.966 --> 35:38.366
(mallet strikes forcefully)

35:38.366 --> 35:40.300
(audience gasps, laughs)

35:40.300 --> 35:41.466
HANKINS:
Tremendous effort, sister!

35:41.466 --> 35:44.200
(laughing):
Were the aim to propel the ball

35:44.200 --> 35:45.700
to the farthest
reaches of the garden,

35:45.700 --> 35:47.200
you would be a clear winner.

35:47.200 --> 35:48.666
(laughing)

35:51.033 --> 35:53.133
Oh, Tom, perhaps you should
introduce me to Mr. Colbourne.

35:53.133 --> 35:54.100
Oh, Mary, no.

35:54.100 --> 35:55.533
The poor man
is all on his own.

35:55.533 --> 35:56.533
But Mary, I...

35:56.533 --> 35:58.500
(stammering)

35:58.500 --> 36:01.433
(exhales)

36:01.433 --> 36:03.433
(crowd applauding)

36:03.433 --> 36:05.066
TOM:
Oh, Mr. Colbourne.

36:06.200 --> 36:08.900
May I introduce
my wife, Mary Parker?

36:08.900 --> 36:10.033
Mrs. Parker.

36:10.033 --> 36:12.400
Delighted to meet you,
Mr. Colbourne.

36:12.400 --> 36:14.033
Tell me, Mr. Parker,
was it your idea

36:14.033 --> 36:15.366
to bring the military
to Sanditon?

36:17.400 --> 36:20.133
I cannot take credit for it,

36:20.133 --> 36:22.500
but I happily agreed to it.

36:22.500 --> 36:23.833
In fact,
I am in the process of

36:23.833 --> 36:24.900
negotiating
a permanent barracks

36:24.900 --> 36:25.866
with Colonel Lennox.

36:25.866 --> 36:28.066
Is that not right,
Colonel?

36:28.066 --> 36:31.633
Negotiating is
rather overstating the case.

36:31.633 --> 36:33.166
I'm yet to be
convinced that

36:33.166 --> 36:34.333
permanent barracks
are a good idea.

36:34.333 --> 36:36.833
(crowd applauding)

36:36.833 --> 36:38.266
(breath trembling)

36:39.800 --> 36:40.766
(exhales)

36:40.766 --> 36:42.600
(crowd murmuring)

36:42.600 --> 36:44.666
Take your hands
off her!
He's trying to help.

36:44.666 --> 36:46.233
Augusta?

36:46.233 --> 36:47.300
Augusta!

36:47.300 --> 36:49.900
Augusta!
Augusta!

36:52.066 --> 36:54.833
CHARLOTTE:
Why did you lace it so tightly?

36:54.833 --> 36:58.433
I wanted gentlemen to
think me pretty.

36:58.433 --> 36:59.733
I wanted to look womanly.

36:59.733 --> 37:01.566
I, I know how foolish
that sounds.

37:01.566 --> 37:03.833
Being able to breathe
is rather more important.

37:03.833 --> 37:06.066
(sighs)

37:06.066 --> 37:07.633
There

37:07.633 --> 37:11.733
is a gentleman
who finds you pretty.

37:11.733 --> 37:13.500
You must have noticed.

37:15.333 --> 37:18.066
Colonel Lennox.

37:18.066 --> 37:20.566
Yet...

37:20.566 --> 37:21.700
(exhales)

37:21.700 --> 37:26.100
I cannot tell if you
welcome his attention.

37:30.366 --> 37:32.833
(people talking,
music playing in background)

37:37.933 --> 37:40.400
It's time to cut my cake.

37:40.400 --> 37:41.733
Mr. Parker,

37:41.733 --> 37:45.200
I remember how keen you were
to cut my pineapple.

37:45.200 --> 37:48.400
Perhaps you would like to
do the honors.

37:48.400 --> 37:50.266
I regret
that I cannot.

37:50.266 --> 37:53.166
Oh.

37:53.166 --> 37:57.166
You would offend your hostess
for the sake of this

37:57.166 --> 37:59.233
absurd sugar boycott?

37:59.233 --> 38:01.500
When will we
hear the end of it?

38:01.500 --> 38:04.800
When every last slave
is freed, milady.

38:06.333 --> 38:08.066
I know you believe me
a hypocrite

38:08.066 --> 38:10.600
because I am a beneficiary
of the very trade

38:10.600 --> 38:11.833
I seek to boycott.

38:11.833 --> 38:13.800
But I cannot
change the past.

38:15.766 --> 38:17.200
All I can do

38:17.200 --> 38:21.933
is speak
for those who cannot.

38:21.933 --> 38:23.500
The fact is,

38:23.500 --> 38:25.566
anyone who buys sugar

38:25.566 --> 38:28.300
perpetuates this evil trade.

38:28.300 --> 38:30.733
So, if you are not
troubled by

38:30.733 --> 38:33.766
the thought of men and women
toiling all day

38:33.766 --> 38:37.333
to harvest your sugar,
then by all means,

38:37.333 --> 38:41.166
enjoy your cake.

38:41.166 --> 38:42.633
But I must decline.

38:43.733 --> 38:47.933
(crowd murmuring)

38:47.933 --> 38:49.666
♪ ♪

38:49.666 --> 38:52.500
(plates clinking)

38:55.366 --> 38:57.066
Oh, this is absurd.

39:02.033 --> 39:03.233
(gasps)

39:03.233 --> 39:07.466
♪ ♪

39:08.766 --> 39:11.366
She is the very image
of her aunt.

39:11.366 --> 39:12.766
When she was in my arms,

39:12.766 --> 39:15.500
it was as if Lucy
had come back to me.

39:20.666 --> 39:23.333
(honking)

39:23.333 --> 39:28.566
♪ ♪

39:42.166 --> 39:47.333
♪ ♪

39:57.400 --> 40:00.166
(exhales)

40:00.166 --> 40:03.066
My dear Alison.

40:03.066 --> 40:05.200
There is a question
I am burning to ask you.

40:05.200 --> 40:06.966
Indeed,

40:06.966 --> 40:09.733
the rest of my life
may depend upon your answer.

40:09.733 --> 40:12.366
Then ask it.

40:14.433 --> 40:17.000
(wood creaking)

40:22.033 --> 40:26.066
Would you do me the honor
of becoming my wife?

40:27.300 --> 40:29.033
(laughing):
Yes, William!

40:29.033 --> 40:30.500
The answer is yes!

40:30.500 --> 40:32.266
(yelps):
Alison!

40:32.266 --> 40:33.500
(splashing)

40:33.500 --> 40:34.500
Alison!

40:34.500 --> 40:36.233
Here!
(gasping, struggling)

40:36.233 --> 40:37.866
I can't, I cannot swim!
Take the oar!

40:37.866 --> 40:39.100
Take, take the oar!

40:39.100 --> 40:40.133
(struggling)

40:40.133 --> 40:41.300
Take the oar!

40:41.300 --> 40:43.333
Help!

40:43.333 --> 40:45.033
(struggling)
Alison!

40:45.033 --> 40:47.400
(gasping)
Help! Help!

40:47.400 --> 40:48.833
(gasping)

40:48.833 --> 40:50.033
(sobbing)

40:50.033 --> 40:52.066
(yelping)

40:53.900 --> 40:55.600
Help!
Someone, please!

40:55.600 --> 40:56.766
Help!

40:57.866 --> 41:00.600
Alison!

41:02.166 --> 41:07.466
(people talking in background)

41:11.500 --> 41:16.900
There is the passion
that I've been looking for.

41:16.900 --> 41:19.700
How I should love
to capture your expression

41:19.700 --> 41:22.333
at this very moment.

41:24.066 --> 41:29.966
I assume you have a pencil,
paper?

41:31.133 --> 41:32.833
Always.

41:35.566 --> 41:37.966
Very well, then.

41:37.966 --> 41:39.000
But not here.

41:39.000 --> 41:41.533
I don't want an audience.

41:41.533 --> 41:46.500
♪ ♪

41:53.566 --> 41:56.066
(retches)

41:56.066 --> 41:58.900
(coughing)

41:58.900 --> 42:02.033
(gasping)

42:02.033 --> 42:04.200
(coughing)

42:04.200 --> 42:05.500
(coughing)

42:05.500 --> 42:07.200
(gasping)

42:11.633 --> 42:12.933
(stammering):
Why was it you?

42:12.933 --> 42:16.166
(gasping)

42:16.166 --> 42:17.566
Why did William not

42:17.566 --> 42:19.233
try to save me?

42:19.233 --> 42:23.466
(breath trembling)

42:25.066 --> 42:27.333
Colonel Lennox?

42:27.333 --> 42:30.700
It's almost time for me
to present the Silver Arrow.

42:30.700 --> 42:33.200
And you have yet
to take up the bow.

42:33.200 --> 42:35.366
Will you not show your men
how it is done?

42:35.366 --> 42:37.233
With pleasure, milady.

42:37.233 --> 42:41.166
We must find you
a worthy adversary.

42:41.166 --> 42:42.633
Mr. Colbourne.

42:42.633 --> 42:45.866
Would you
consider some sport?

42:45.866 --> 42:48.266
Will you take up
the bow against me?

42:49.500 --> 42:51.533
No.
Thank you.

42:51.533 --> 42:54.433
LADY DENHAM:
Oh, that's rather ungracious
of you, Mr. Colbourne.

42:54.433 --> 42:58.500
Are you afraid the colonel
might show you up?

42:58.500 --> 43:05.766
♪ ♪

43:11.566 --> 43:13.633
MARY:
Why will you not just
address the matter?

43:14.900 --> 43:18.500
What is this hold
he has over you?

43:18.500 --> 43:19.866
I've a good mind
to speak to him myself.

43:19.866 --> 43:21.566
(sharply):
No.

43:21.566 --> 43:23.066
Uh, thank you, Mary, no.

43:23.066 --> 43:26.433
Uh, better he and I
resolve things ourselves.

43:26.433 --> 43:28.800
Uh, I need to go
and seek out Arthur.

43:28.800 --> 43:31.866
I think he's by
the drinks.

43:31.866 --> 43:33.566
(talking in background)

43:33.566 --> 43:39.933
♪ ♪

43:43.233 --> 43:45.300
(crowd gasping, applauding)

43:45.300 --> 43:46.333
LADY DENHAM:
Ooh!

43:46.333 --> 43:48.733
A fine start, Colonel.

43:48.733 --> 43:49.866
Mr. Colbourne,

43:49.866 --> 43:52.066
you'll be lucky to match it.

43:55.233 --> 43:58.500
♪ ♪

44:03.800 --> 44:05.066
(crowd gasping)

44:05.066 --> 44:06.600
LADY DENHAM:
Oh, I spoke too soon.

44:06.600 --> 44:08.433
This will be
a fight to the death.

44:08.433 --> 44:10.100
(applauding)

44:10.800 --> 44:12.200
Aunt.

44:12.200 --> 44:13.966
(applause fades)

44:15.800 --> 44:17.233
Edward!

44:17.233 --> 44:18.533
What is the meaning
of this?

44:18.533 --> 44:20.433
How dare you turn up
uninvited!

44:20.433 --> 44:22.166
Forgive me, Aunt--
I couldn't wait a moment longer

44:22.166 --> 44:23.666
to share my good news
with you both.

44:25.200 --> 44:27.700
Clara's agreed to
do me the great honor

44:27.700 --> 44:29.166
of becoming my wife.

44:29.166 --> 44:33.866
♪ ♪

44:36.066 --> 44:38.500
(crowd murmuring)

44:38.500 --> 44:40.300
You cannot swim.

44:40.300 --> 44:41.866
You would have
let me drown.

44:41.866 --> 44:43.166
No, no.

44:43.166 --> 44:44.400
When Captain Fraser arrived,

44:44.400 --> 44:45.966
I was just about to dive in...
Stop!

44:45.966 --> 44:48.100
No more lies!

44:48.100 --> 44:49.133
Charlotte was right.

44:49.133 --> 44:51.200
You were never at Bidassoa,
were you?

44:52.800 --> 44:54.300
Was he?

44:55.833 --> 44:57.366
It is not my place to say.

44:57.366 --> 44:59.700
Was any of it true?

45:02.700 --> 45:04.800
My feelings for you
are true.

45:05.933 --> 45:08.566
You are nothing but a coward.

45:10.200 --> 45:12.566
And I'm nothing but a fool.

45:14.400 --> 45:16.566
And you.

45:16.566 --> 45:17.666
You knew,

45:17.666 --> 45:20.766
and you said nothing.

45:20.766 --> 45:21.900
(sniffs)

45:24.633 --> 45:28.300
♪ ♪

45:28.300 --> 45:29.333
What are you thinking?

45:29.333 --> 45:31.066
We are thinking of our son.

45:31.066 --> 45:33.466
This will make him respectable,
bring him security.

45:33.466 --> 45:35.266
I grew up with Edward.

45:35.266 --> 45:37.400
I would not wish him upon
my worst enemy.

45:37.400 --> 45:39.366
If your concern
is really for the child,

45:39.366 --> 45:41.266
you should be pleased.

45:41.266 --> 45:42.766
He will not be a bastard.

45:42.766 --> 45:44.166
He may take the Denham name.

45:44.166 --> 45:45.400
And the Denham money?

45:47.400 --> 45:49.266
Our aunt will
see through this sham,

45:49.266 --> 45:50.966
just as I do.

45:52.800 --> 45:54.533
You have Edward quite wrong.

45:55.733 --> 45:57.833
He is not the man he was.

45:57.833 --> 46:00.300
He has become considerate.

46:00.300 --> 46:01.566
Honorable.

46:01.566 --> 46:02.900
(George crying)
(sighs)

46:03.800 --> 46:05.266
(sighs)

46:05.266 --> 46:06.633
Martha!

46:10.000 --> 46:12.466
Martha!
Where is she?

46:12.466 --> 46:14.466
He needs feeding, Clara.
(George crying)

46:14.466 --> 46:16.366
Then he will
have to wait.

46:16.366 --> 46:18.700
(bawling)

46:18.700 --> 46:20.766
Your child
needs his mother.

46:20.766 --> 46:22.266
Don't you see?

46:22.266 --> 46:24.866
I cannot be his mother!
(bawling continues)

46:24.866 --> 46:27.666
All the things
a mother is

46:27.666 --> 46:29.966
I am not.

46:34.266 --> 46:37.433
(applauding,
murmuring in approval)

46:45.366 --> 46:46.700
It occurs to me...

46:47.800 --> 46:49.433
Why should we men
have all the fun?

46:51.433 --> 46:53.200
I nominate Miss Heywood

46:53.200 --> 46:55.233
to take my final shot.

46:57.133 --> 46:58.533
Thank you, Colonel,

46:58.533 --> 47:00.400
but this contest is between
you and Mr. Colbourne.

47:00.400 --> 47:02.533
I insist.

47:07.533 --> 47:08.633
(exhales)

47:08.633 --> 47:14.733
♪ ♪

47:14.733 --> 47:16.133
(softly):
Mrs. Parker,

47:16.133 --> 47:17.666
I cannot find Miss Lambe.

47:17.666 --> 47:19.266
She is nowhere to be found.

47:19.266 --> 47:21.166
(breath trembles)

47:23.800 --> 47:27.933
(animal calling, birds chirping)

47:31.233 --> 47:34.433
Otis Molyneux.

47:36.300 --> 47:41.333
That is who I dreamed of
last night.

47:41.333 --> 47:43.933
Who is he?

47:43.933 --> 47:48.300
The only man
I have ever loved.

47:48.300 --> 47:51.600
It was him who introduced me
to the sugar boycott.

47:53.466 --> 47:54.600
(exhales)

47:54.600 --> 47:57.100
But we parted badly.

47:57.100 --> 47:58.200
He let me down.

47:58.200 --> 48:02.133
Perhaps that is why

48:02.133 --> 48:05.733
I'm reluctant
to lower my guard.

48:05.733 --> 48:07.733
To let myself be seen.

48:09.800 --> 48:12.066
(places pad down)

48:12.066 --> 48:13.733
(exhales)

48:13.733 --> 48:16.066
(softly):
So why do you
still dream of him?

48:20.233 --> 48:23.066
Because I have no one
else to dream of.

48:26.500 --> 48:31.866
♪ ♪

48:35.666 --> 48:36.966
Miss Lambe!

48:36.966 --> 48:40.033
We have been
looking for you everywhere!

48:40.033 --> 48:43.333
And now
you have found me.

48:47.500 --> 48:49.700
(George crying)
ESTHER:
What are you so afraid of?

48:49.700 --> 48:52.466
I am scared
to let myself love him.

48:54.200 --> 48:57.500
What it would mean,
for both of us.

49:06.800 --> 49:08.833
Look at him, Clara.

49:16.333 --> 49:19.166
(exhales)

49:19.166 --> 49:21.533
Bring him close.

49:21.533 --> 49:23.033
(squawking)

49:23.033 --> 49:25.100
(exhales)

49:25.100 --> 49:26.500
(squawking softens)

49:26.500 --> 49:29.000
Offer yourself to him.
(George fussing)

49:29.000 --> 49:31.666
(crying stops)

49:31.666 --> 49:32.800
He will find you.

49:32.800 --> 49:33.900
(winces)

49:35.366 --> 49:39.166
♪ ♪

49:39.166 --> 49:41.166
(gasping)

49:43.200 --> 49:45.200
(exhales)

49:47.400 --> 49:50.400
You are a better
woman than you think.

49:53.733 --> 49:57.566
(murmuring)

49:57.566 --> 50:00.900
You must make the tension tight,
keep it strong.

50:02.766 --> 50:07.133
This is not the first time
I've used a bow.

50:08.733 --> 50:15.566
♪ ♪

50:15.566 --> 50:16.600
(crowd gasping)
Oh, heavens.

50:16.600 --> 50:19.100
(crowd applauding)

50:19.100 --> 50:20.933
Well played, Miss Heywood.

50:21.900 --> 50:23.366
I am lucky
to have you on my side.

50:25.933 --> 50:27.800
Why should the colonel
gain an unfair advantage?

50:29.966 --> 50:34.533
Miss Heywood,
would you do me the same honor?

50:34.533 --> 50:41.800
♪ ♪

50:52.833 --> 50:56.233
(crowd murmuring)

50:56.233 --> 50:58.733
(crowd groaning)

50:58.733 --> 50:59.766
LADY DENHAM:
Oh!

50:59.766 --> 51:01.666
(crowd applauding)

51:01.666 --> 51:03.433
Well, Colonel Lennox
is the winner,

51:03.433 --> 51:05.433
but I'm not sure this counts.

51:05.433 --> 51:06.866
(applause fades)

51:06.866 --> 51:08.100
LENNOX:
Never mind, Mr. Colbourne.

51:11.700 --> 51:14.500
You know what they say:
all's fair in love and war.

51:14.500 --> 51:18.100
But then, I've known both
and you've known neither.

51:25.566 --> 51:27.733
We're leaving.

51:31.200 --> 51:32.100
(gasps)

51:32.100 --> 51:34.133
CHARLOTTE:
Mr. Colbourne!

51:36.566 --> 51:37.666
You are not to spend
another minute

51:37.666 --> 51:38.633
in that man's company.

51:38.633 --> 51:39.966
That is not your
decision to make.

51:39.966 --> 51:42.333
You are my governess--
I forbid it!

51:43.833 --> 51:45.100
You might pay my wages,

51:45.100 --> 51:46.400
but I am not yours
to order about.

51:47.900 --> 51:49.366
You do not own me.

51:49.366 --> 51:53.033
♪ ♪

51:53.033 --> 51:54.500
(pounds ceiling)

51:54.500 --> 51:58.066
(carriage moving)

51:58.066 --> 52:02.533
♪ ♪

52:16.033 --> 52:17.300
♪ ♪

52:17.300 --> 52:19.700
ALISON:
One of us deserves to find
happiness.

52:19.700 --> 52:20.866
Colonel Lennox is a good man.

52:20.866 --> 52:22.566
CHARLES:
You changed your hair.

52:22.566 --> 52:25.500
GEORGIANA:
This is how I wish
to be seen.

52:25.500 --> 52:27.600
MRS. WHEATLEY:
There is more to
Alexander Colbourne

52:27.600 --> 52:29.366
than you can possibly imagine.

52:29.366 --> 52:31.666
I must know who you are.

52:31.666 --> 52:34.533
♪ ♪

52:36.000 --> 52:39.900
♪ ♪

